Geospatial Risk Prediction

Yingxue Ou

10/20/2022

Introduction

In this project, I will build spatial variables in fishnet raster-like grid and run local Morans I as a measure of local clustering. And then, run a poisson regression to predict events measured in counts. Finally, I will compare model performance of Kernal Density as a business-as-usual alternative.

Setup

Begin by loading the requisite packages and functions, including the functions.R script.

2 A map of outcome joined to the fishnet.

Creating a fishnet grid

Here I using sf to created 500ft by 500ftfishnet called chicagoBoundary that omits OHare airport in the northwest of the city.

## using {sf} to create the grid
fishnet <- 
  st_make_grid(chicagoBoundary,
               cellsize = 500, 
               square = TRUE) %>%
  .[chicagoBoundary] %>%            # fast way to select intersecting polygons
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(uniqueID = 1:n())

Aggregate points to the fishnet

To count the weapons violation by grid cell, first mutate a counter field, countWeapon, for each weapon violation event, and then spatial join (aggregate) weapon violation points to the fishnet, taking the sum of countWeapon. A grid cell with no weapon violation receives NA which is converted to 0 with replace_na. A random uniqueID is generated for each grid cell, as well as a random group cvID, used later for cross-validation. Roughly 100 cvIDs are created to allow 100-fold cross validation. Map below show the counts of weapons violation by grid cell, and the clustered spatial process of weapon violation begins to take shape.

## add a value of 1 to each crime, sum them with aggregate
crime_net <- 
  dplyr::select(weapon) %>% 
  mutate(countWeapon = 1) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(countWeapon = replace_na(countWeapon, 0),
         uniqueID = 1:n(),
         cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 24), 
                       size=nrow(fishnet), replace = TRUE))

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = crime_net, aes(fill = countWeapon), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis() +
  labs(title = "Count of Weapon Violation for the fishnet") +
  mapTheme()

Count of risk factor by grid cell

Here I joined a long form of layer of crime events to the vars_net fishnet.

vars_net <- 
  rbind(abandonCars,streetLightsOut,abandonBuildings,
        liquorRetail, alleyLightsOut, rodentBait, graffiti, sanitation) %>%
  st_join(., fishnet, join=st_within) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  group_by(uniqueID, Legend) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
    full_join(fishnet) %>%
    spread(Legend, count, fill=0) %>%
    st_sf() %>%
    dplyr::select(-`<NA>`) %>%
    na.omit() %>%
    ungroup()

4 Local Morans I-related small multiple map of your outcome (see 5.4.1)

Creating final_net

Next, the crime_net and vars_net layers are joined into one regression-ready, final_net.

## important to drop the geometry from joining features
final_net <-
  left_join(crime_net, st_drop_geometry(vars_net), by="uniqueID")

Join in areal data

Neighborhood name and policeDistrict are spatially joined to the final_net using grid cell centroids.

final_net <-
  st_centroid(final_net) %>%
    st_join(dplyr::select(neighborhoods, name), by = "uniqueID") %>%
    st_join(dplyr::select(policeDistricts, District), by = "uniqueID") %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(dplyr::select(final_net, geometry, uniqueID)) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
  na.omit()

Local Morans I

Here I use {spdep} package to to build neighborhood weights and list to calculate local Morans I.

final_net.nb <- poly2nb(as_Spatial(final_net), queen=TRUE)

final_net.weights <- nb2listw(final_net.nb, style="W", zero.policy=TRUE)
## see ?localmoran
local_morans <- localmoran(final_net$countWeapon, final_net.weights, zero.policy=TRUE) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

# join local Moran's I results to fishnet
final_net.localMorans <- 
  cbind(local_morans, as.data.frame(final_net)) %>% 
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(countWeapon = countWeapon, 
                Local_Morans_I = Ii, 
                P_Value = `Pr(z != E(Ii))`) %>%
  mutate(Significant_Hotspots = ifelse(P_Value <= 0.001, 1, 0)) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -geometry)

Plotting local Morans I results

## This is just for plotting
vars <- unique(final_net.localMorans$Variable)
varList <- list()

for(i in vars){
  varList[[i]] <- 
    ggplot() +
      geom_sf(data = filter(final_net.localMorans, Variable == i), 
              aes(fill = Value), colour=NA) +
      scale_fill_viridis(name="") +
      labs(title=i) +
      mapTheme(title_size = 14) + theme(legend.position="bottom")}

do.call(grid.arrange,c(varList, ncol = 4, top = "Local Morans I statistics, Weapon Violation"))

# 7 Map of model errors by random k-fold and spatial cross validation

Join NN feature to our fishnet

Here I calculated NN of each variable by setting K=3.

# nearest neighborhood features

st_c <- st_coordinates
st_coid <- st_centroid

final_net <-
  final_net %>%
  mutate(
    Abandoned_Buildings.nn = 
      nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)), st_c(abandonBuildings), 3),
    Abandoned_Cars.nn = 
      nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)), st_c(abandonCars), 3),
    AlleyLightsOut.nn = 
      nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)), st_c(alleyLightsOut), 3),
    Liquor_Retail.nn = 
      nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)), st_c(liquorRetail), 3),
    RodentBaiting.nn = 
      nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)), st_c(rodentBait), 3),
    Street_Lights_Out.nn =
      nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)), st_c(streetLightsOut), 3),
    Sanitation.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)), st_c(sanitation),3),
    Graffiti.nn =
        nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)), st_c(graffiti),3))

Using NN distance to a hot spot location of each variables.

 # generates warning from NN
final_net <- final_net %>% 
  mutate(weapon.isSig =

           nn_function(st_c(st_coid(final_net)),

                       k = 1))
reg.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "AlleyLightsOut.nn", 
              "Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "RodentBaiting.nn",

              "loopDistance")

reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "AlleyLightsOut.nn", 
                 "Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "RodentBaiting.nn",

                 "loopDistance", "weapon.isSig", "weapon.isSig.dist")

I generated four regressions below - two including Just Risk Factors(reg.vars), and a second (reg.ss.vars) includes risk factors plus the Local Morans I Spatial Process features created above.

reg.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countWeapon",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countWeapon, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countWeapon",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countWeapon, Prediction, geometry)
  
reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countWeapon",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countWeapon, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countWeapon",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countWeapon, Prediction, geometry)
reg.summary <- 
  rbind(
    mutate(reg.cv,           Error = Prediction - countWeapon,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.cv,        Error = Prediction - countWeapon,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Process"),
    
    mutate(reg.spatialCV,    Error = Prediction - countWeapon,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.spatialCV, Error = Prediction - countWeapon,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Process")) %>%
    st_sf()

In the code block below, error_by_reg_and_fold calculates and visualizes MAE for each fold across each regression. The Spatial Process features seem to reduce errors overall.

error_by_reg_and_fold <- 
  reg.summary %>%
    group_by(Regression, cvID) %>% 
    summarize(Mean_Error = mean(Prediction - countWeapon, na.rm = T),
              MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T),
              SD_MAE = mean(abs(Mean_Error), na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup()

Plot a multiple map of model errors

error_by_reg_and_fold %>%
  filter(str_detect(Regression, "LOGO")) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = MAE)) +
    facet_wrap(~Regression) +
    scale_fill_viridis() +
    labs(title = "Weapon Violation errors by LOGO-CV Regression") +
    mapTheme() + theme(legend.position="bottom")

9 A table of raw errors by race context

To test if the algorithm generalize across different neighborhood contexts, I used tidycensus to pull race data by Census tract. percentWhite is calculated and tracts are split into two groups, Majority_White and Majority_Non_White. A spatial subset is used to get tracts within the study area.

tracts18 <- 
  get_acs(geography = "tract", variables = c("B01001_001E","B01001A_001E"), 
          year = 2018, state=17, county=031, geometry=T) %>%
  st_transform('ESRI:102271')  %>% 
  dplyr::select(variable, estimate, GEOID) %>%
  spread(variable, estimate) %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B01001_001,
         NumberWhites = B01001A_001) %>%
  mutate(percentWhite = NumberWhites / TotalPop,
         raceContext = ifelse(percentWhite > .5, "Majority_White", "Majority_Non_White")) %>%
  .[neighborhoods,]

Now, create a Kernel density map with a 1000ft search redius using the spatstat package. as.ppp converts burglary coordinates to a ppp class. The density function creates the Kernel density. To map, the ppp is converted to a data frame and then an sf layer. Points are spatially joined to the final_net and the mean density is taken. Here density is visualized with a sample_n of 1,500 points overlayed on top.

as.data.frame(weapon_KD.1000) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("x", "y"), crs = st_crs(final_net)) %>%
  aggregate(., final_net, mean) %>%

     geom_sf(aes(fill=value)) +

     scale_fill_viridis(name = "Density") +

11 The bar plot making this comparison.

Finally, the code block below calculates the rate of 2018 weapons violation points by risk category and model type. A well fit model should show that the risk predictions capture a greater share of 2018 burglaries in the middle risk category relative to the Kernel density.

rbind(weapon_KDE_sf, weapon_risk_sf) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  na.omit() %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -label, -Risk_Category) %>%
  group_by(label, Risk_Category) %>%
  summarize(weaponCount = sum(Value)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(label) %>%
  mutate(Pcnt_of_test_set_crimes = weaponCount / sum(weaponCount)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(Risk_Category,Pcnt_of_test_set_crimes)) +
      geom_bar(aes(fill=label), position="dodge", stat="identity") +
      scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, name = "Model") +
      labs(title = "Risk prediction vs. Kernel density, 2018 Weapon Violation",
           y = "% of Test Set Theft (per model)",
           x = "Risk Category") +
  theme_bw() +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 0.5))

12 Two paragraphs on why or why not you would recommend your algorithm be put into production.

In conclusion, I would like to recommend my algorithm be put into production. The geospatial risk prediction model borrows the weapon violation in places where it has benn observed, and tests whether that experience generalizes to places where weapons violation risk may be middle high. If these tests are successful, the results predictions can be thought of as latent risk for weapons violation and can be used to allocate police response.

By introducing new features engineering stratrgies to capture the local spatial process and spatial cross-validation as an important test of across-space generalizability. It is believed that even a simple risk prediction algorithm may outperform traditional hot spot analysis. By adding the element of time/seasonality and deploying predictions in an intuitive user interface, this approach could have better competitive in commercial predictive policing products.
